to the editor your article altered tomato thrives in salty soil aug 14 highlighted a promising application of biotechnology but failed to mention two roadblocks first industry has shown little interest in commercializing genetically engineered minor crops like fruits and vegetables instead it has focused on major market crops like cotton corn and soybeans even if this tomato is safe for consumers and the environment who will take it to market second the noisy controversy over biotechnology has scared farmers away from growing engineered sugar beets apples sweet corn and other crops that need fewer or safer pesticides and cause less soil erosion if this tomato is marketed will anyone grow or buy it safe applications of biotechnology offer tremendous benefits but until our society answers those questions those benefits may be lost gregory jaffe washington the writer is with the center for science in the public interest

